#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:13
msgid "You can select and edit bones of armatures in *Edit Mode* and in *Pose Mode*. Here, we will see how to select bones in *Edit Mode*. Selecting bones in *Pose Mode* is similar to selecting in *Edit Mode* with a few specific differences that will be detailed in the :doc:`posing part </rigging/armatures/posing/editing>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:18
msgid "Similar to :doc:`vertices/edges selection </modeling/meshes/selecting/introduction>` in meshes, there are two ways to select whole bones in *Edit Mode*:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:21
msgid "Directly, by selecting the bone's body."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:22
msgid "Selecting both of its joints (root and tip)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:24
msgid "This is an important point to understand, because selecting bones' joints only might lead to non-obvious behavior, with respect to which bone you actually select, see the."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:28
msgid "Note that unlike the mesh draw type the armature draw type has no effect on selection behavior. In other words, you can select a bone's joint or body the same way regardless of the bone visualization chosen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:34
msgid "Selecting bone joints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:36
msgid "To select bones' joints you have the :doc:`standard selection </editors/3dview/object/selecting>` methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:40
msgid "Inverse selection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:42
msgid "As stated above, you have to remember that these selection tools are for bones' joints only, not the bones' bodies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:45
msgid "For example, the *Inverse* selection option :kbd:`Ctrl-I` inverts the selection of bones' joints, not of bones (see *Inverse selection*)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:48
msgid "Remember that a bone is selected only if both its joints are selected. So, when the selection status of bones' joints is inverted, a new set of bones is selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst
msgid "Inverse selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:56
msgid "Two bones selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:61
msgid "The result of the inverse selection :kbd:`Ctrl-I` the bones joints selection has been inverted, and not the bones selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:66
msgid "Selecting connected bone joints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:68
msgid "Another example is: when you select the root of a bone connected to its parent, you also implicitly select the tip of its parent (and vice versa)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:73
msgid "Remember that when selecting bones' joints, the tip of the parent bone is the \"same thing\" as the root of its children bones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:78
msgid "Selecting Bones"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:80
msgid "By :kbd:`RMB` -clicking on a bone's body, you will select it (and hence you will implicitly select its root and tip)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:83
msgid "Using :kbd:`Shift-RMB`, you can add to/remove from the selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:85
msgid "You also have some *advanced selection* options, based on their relations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/rigging/armatures/bones/selecting.rst:87
msgid "You can select at once all the bones in the chain which the active (last selected) bone belongs to by using the *linked selection* tool, :kbd:`L`."
msgstr ""

